'''''Infinite Energy''''' is a bi-monthly magazine published in [[New Hampshire]] that details theories and experiments concerning [[alternative energy]], new science and new physics. The magazine was founded by the late [[Eugene Mallove]], and is owned by the non-profit [[New Energy Foundation]].<ref name=iemission>[http://www.infinite-energy.com/whoarewe/whoarewe.html Infinite Energy: What is the New Energy Foundation?]</ref> It was established in 1994 as ''Cold Fusion'' magazine <ref>[http://www.nashuatelegraph.com/csp/cms/sites/Telegraph/granitegeek/archive2010/index.csp Before 'Infinite Energy' it was 'Cold Fusion']</ref> and changed its name in March 1995.<ref>[http://www.infinite-energy.com/iemagazine/aboutthemagazine.html About the magazine]</ref>
Topics of interest include "new hydrogen physics," also called [[cold fusion]]; vacuum energy, or [[zero point energy]]; and so-called "environmental energy" which they define as the attempt to violate the [[Second Law of Thermodynamics]],<ref>[http://www.infinite-energy.com/resources/faq.html#Q34 Infinite Energy FAQ: Environmental energy]</ref> for example with a [http://www.infinite-energy.com/resources/faq.html#Q40 perpetual motion machine]. This is done in pursuit of the founder's commitment to "unearthing new sources of energy and new paradigms in science."<ref name=iemission /> The magazine has also published articles and book reviews that are critical of the [[big bang]] theory that describes the [[Physical cosmology|origin of the universe]].
The magazine has a [[print run]] of 3,000, and is available on U.S. newsstands. The issues range in size from 48 to 100 pages.
