A '''Plumage League''' to campaign against the excessive use of birds' feathers and plumage in ladies fashions was formed by [[Francis Orpen Morris|Reverend Francis Orpen Morris]] and [[ Georgiana Cowper-Temple, Lady Mount Temple|Lady Mount Temple]] in December 1885.<ref name=SS>{{citation |title=The Selborne Society |author=Michael Blackmore |year=1985 |url=http://perivalewood.k-hosting.co.uk/blackmore.pdf |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027151840/http://perivalewood.k-hosting.co.uk/blackmore.pdf |archivedate=2014-10-27 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{citation |page=4 |title=Reclaiming Paradise: The Global Environmental Movement |author=John McCormick |publisher=Indiana University Press |year=1991 |isbn=9780253206602}}</ref> This almost immediately amalgamated to form the [[Plumage Section]] of the [[Selborne Society for the Preservation of Birds, Plants and Pleasant Places]] in the following January.<ref name=SS/>
Another plumage league was later formed by Emily Williamson in [[Didsbury]]. This was organised by Mancunian women unable to join the male [[British Ornithological Union]] as the [[Society for Protection of Birds]] which subsequently became the [[RSPB]].<ref>{{citation |page=862 |title=Victorian Britain: An Encyclopedia |author=Sally Mitchell |publisher=Routledge |year=2012 |isbn=9781136716171}}</ref><ref>{{citation |page=44 |work=Environmental Politics in the International Arena: Movements, Parties, Organizations, and Policy |author=Russel J Dalton |publisher=SUNY Press |year=1993 |isbn=9780791416631 |title=The Environmental Movement in Western Europe}}</ref>
