[[File:Suez Canal overhead line crossing.jpg|thumb|Overhead line crossing]] The '''Suez Canal overhead powerline crossing''' is a major [[Electric power transmission|electrical power line]] built across the [[Suez Canal]] in 1998, located near [[Suez]], [[Egypt]]. It is designed for two 500 kV circuits.
Because the required clearance over the Suez Canal is {{convert|152|m|ft}}, the overhead line has two {{convert|221|m|ft}} high [[Electricity pylon|pylon]]s (one on either side of the crossing) in spite of its small span width of {{convert|600|m|ft}}. The pylons each have four crossarms: three for the [[conductor (material)|conductor]]s and one for catching the conductors in case of an [[Electrical insulation|insulator]] string failure.
==Significant developments in the region== The crossing was part of a major drive to develop the areas surrounding the [[Suez Canal]], including other projects such as the [[Ahmed Hamdi Tunnel]] under the Suez Canal (completed in 1981), the [[El Ferdan Railway Bridge]], and the [[Suez Canal Bridge]] (completed in 2001).
It was constructed by a consortium between STFA Enerkom and [[Siemens]].<ref>http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=83301</ref>
