{{about|the sea nymph|the sponge genus|Thoosa (sponge)}}
{{Infobox deity | type = Greek | name = Thoosa | image = | alt = | caption = Mother of Polyphemos | god_of = | abode = | symbol = | consort = [[Poseidon]] | parents = [[Phorcys]] and [[Ceto]] | siblings = {{hlist|[[Gorgon]]s|[[Graeae]]|[[Hesperides]]|[[Echidna (mythology)|Echidna]]|[[Scylla]]}} | children = [[Polyphemus]] | mount = | Roman_equivalent = }} {{Greek myth (sea)}} In [[Greek mythology]], '''Thoosa''' or '''Thoösa''' ({{IPAc-en|θ|oʊ|ˈ|oʊ|s|ə}}, {{lang-el|text=Θόωσα|translit=Thoôsa}}) was a [[Nereid|sea nymph]] whose name derives from the word ''thoos'', meaning "swift".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theoi.com/Nymphe/NympheThoosa.html |title=Thoosa: Sicilian Sea Nymph of Greek Mythology |website=[[Theoi Project]] |access-date=2017-12-15}}</ref> She and the god [[Poseidon]] are the parents of the [[cyclops]] [[Polyphemus]].<ref>[[Odyssey]]. Book I. Lines 70–72.</ref> According to [[Homer]], Thoosa was the daughter of the [[Greek sea gods|sea god]] [[Phorcys]], but no mother is mentioned.
